      "cause": "Both R1 and R3 have static/host routes for 172.16.0.0/24 that point at each other (R1 -> 10.0.0.9, R3 -> 10.0.0.10). Traffic from 192.168.0.12 destined to 172.16.0.12 will be forwarded R1->R3 then R3->R1 instead of toward the actual network, producing a forwarding loop/blackhole and causing all pings to fail.",
      "evidence": [
        "R1 routing entry: prefix 172.16.0.0 mask 255.255.255.0 fwd-list: fwd = 10.0.0.9 (ToolMessage: get_running_config for R1)",
        "R3 routing entry: prefix 172.16.0.0 mask 255.255.255.0 fwd-list: fwd = 10.0.0.10 (ToolMessage: get_running_config for R3)",
        "Interface addressing shows R1 Serial0/1/1 = 10.0.0.10 and R3 Serial0/1/0 = 10.0.0.9 (matching the above next-hops), so each router points the 172.16.0.0/24 next-hop at the other router."
      ],
      "confidence": 0.90
    },
    {
      "type": "Down/unreachable intermediate router",
      "cause": "The intermediate router (router2) that likely hosts or connects the 172.16.0.0/24 network is unreachable, so the true path to 172.16.0.12 is not available.",
